President Barack Obama announced the appointment of Adolfo Carrion as the White House Director of Urban Affairs and Derek Douglas as the Special Assistant to the President for Urban Affairs. The creation of the White House Office of Urban Affairs aims to develop a strategy for metropolitan America and ensure effective spending of federal dollars on impactful programs in urban areas. Adolfo Carrion, former Bronx Borough President, oversaw various urban development projects and has a background in urban planning. Derek Douglas, former Washington Counsel to New York Governor David A. Paterson, has experience in federal policy development and advocacy on economic and urban issues.